---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
const insureBody = `
  

  <!-- ============ SECTION 0: HERO ============ -->
  <header class="hero hero--with-image">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="hero-grid">
        <div class="hero-text">
          <div class="hero-eyebrow eyebrow">Insurance Agent Mortgages</div>
          <h1 class="display-1">Insurance agent mortgage from a lender who reads captive W-2 + commission, independent agent Schedule C, renewal residual income, agency principal K-1, carrier profit sharing, and book-of-business economics as one income picture.</h1>
          <p class="lead hero-subtitle">Working insurance professionals carry one of the most stream-diversified self-employment profiles in sales &mdash; with renewal economics that make a 5-year-old book of business look like an annuity. <strong>Per BLS OOH May 2024 data, insurance sales agents run a median wage of $63,090 with top 10% over $135,100. These numbers understate working producer earnings: established Property &amp; Casualty (P&amp;C) agents commonly earn $150K&ndash;$400K through new commission plus renewal trail, life insurance top producers on the Million Dollar Round Table Top of the Table list earn $300K&ndash;$1M+ through high first-year commission on whole life, IUL, universal life, and annuity products, commercial insurance specialists handling large account books $200K&ndash;$600K through high-per-account commission on commercial P&amp;C, agency principals at independent agencies $250K&ndash;$1M+ through personal production plus sub-producer override plus carrier profit sharing, and multi-state agency owners $500K&ndash;$3M+ through book-of-business scale</strong>. Channel structure splits sharply: captive agents at State Farm, Allstate, Farmers, American Family, Liberty Mutual, and Nationwide receive W-2 base salary plus commission plus bonus through restricted single-carrier relationships; independent agents at Brown &amp; Brown, Marsh McLennan Agency (MMA), HUB International, USI Insurance Services, Acrisure, AssuredPartners, plus thousands of regional and local independent agencies receive 1099-NEC Schedule C commission with multi-carrier flexibility and customer ownership. <strong>Critical contrast: insurance agents are NOT eligible for Physician/Doctor Loan products (similar to realtors, MLOs, pharmacists, vets) &mdash; the optimal path is properly-structured Conventional with channel-appropriate documentation: B3-3.1-01 W-2 for captive agents, B3-3.3-02 Schedule C with Form 1084 addbacks for independent agents, B3-3.4-02 S-corp + K-1 for agency principals, plus multi-source aggregation of renewal income streams that generalist underwriting routinely misses.</strong></p>
          <div class="hero-actions">
            <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/schedule-call" class="btn btn-primary btn-large">Talk to Our Team</a>
            <a href="#income-methods" class="btn btn-secondary btn-large">See how insurance agent qualifying works</a>
          </div>
          <div class="hero-trust">
            <span class="trust-dot"></span>
            <span>Broker NMLS #1072866</span>
            <span>&middot;</span>
            <span>Specialist in insurance agent mortgages &mdash; captive W-2, independent 1099, agency principal S-corp, renewal income, profit sharing, MDRT/CPCU/CLU credentialed top producer income, &amp; PE consolidation rollover equity</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <figure class="hero-image">
          <img src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/8867434/pexels-photo-8867434.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=1200" alt="Insurance agent meeting with clients to review policy" loading="lazy" onerror="this.onerror=null;this.src='https://placehold.co/1200x1500/0A0E1A/E8EEFF/png?text=Insurance';">
        </figure>
      </div>
    </div>
  </header>

  <!-- ============ STATS BAR ============ -->
  <section class="stats stats--with-image">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="stats-bar-grid">
        <div class="stats-grid">
          <div class="stat">
            <div class="stat-num">$150K-$1M+</div>
            <div class="stat-label">Established working insurance agent income range across product lines (P&amp;C $150K-$400K, life MDRT $300K-$1M+, commercial $200K-$600K, agency principals $250K-$1M+)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="stat">
            <div class="stat-num">Renewal income</div>
            <div class="stat-label">Multi-year trailing commission on existing book of business (typically 5-15% of renewing premiums on P&amp;C, lower on life after year 1) &mdash; the stability foundation under variable new business</div>
          </div>
          <div class="stat">
            <div class="stat-num">1.5x-3x</div>
            <div class="stat-label">Book-of-business asset value as multiple of annual revenue (book sale economics support agency principal qualifying through reserve documentation)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="stat">
            <div class="stat-num">2 channels</div>
            <div class="stat-label">Captive (W-2 at State Farm, Allstate, Farmers, Liberty Mutual, Nationwide) vs independent (1099 at Brown &amp; Brown, HUB, USI, Acrisure, regional agencies) &mdash; the central qualifying classification</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <figure class="stats-bar-image">
          <img src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/5668858/pexels-photo-5668858.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=1000" alt="Insurance agent reviewing policy documents" loading="lazy" onerror="this.onerror=null;this.src='https://placehold.co/1000x750/0A0E1A/E8EEFF/png?text=Agents';">
        </figure>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ LEDE ============ -->
  <section class="lede-section">
    <div class="container-narrow">
      <p class="lede">Stairway Mortgage qualifies working insurance agents on the full income picture &mdash; <strong>captive agent W-2 base salary plus commission plus production bonus at State Farm, Allstate, Farmers, American Family, Liberty Mutual, and Nationwide under Fannie Mae B3-3.1-01 as variable income with 24-month average, independent agent 1099-NEC Schedule C commission from Brown &amp; Brown, Marsh McLennan Agency, HUB International, USI Insurance Services, Acrisure, AssuredPartners, and regional independent agencies under Fannie Mae B3-3.3-02 with 2-year averaging plus Form 1084 cash-flow addbacks, multi-year renewal and residual income from existing book of business as the central stability stream, carrier profit-sharing distributions from independent agencies tied to portfolio loss ratios under B3-3.3-02 with 2-year history, agency principal S-corp W-2 reasonable compensation plus K-1 distributions under B3-3.4-02 from Form 1120-S combining personal production with sub-producer override at typically 20-40 percent of sub-producer commission, multi-line specialist income from agents holding combined P&amp;C plus life plus health insurance licenses plus Series 6 or Series 7 for variable annuity products, Medicare Advantage and Medicare Supplement enrollment commission for agents with Annual Enrollment Period (AEP October 15 to December 7) production cycles, book-of-business equity reserves valued at 1.5x to 3x annual revenue supporting reserve documentation, professional designation credentials (CPCU, CIC, CLU, ChFC, CFP, MDRT Top of the Table) supporting the high-tier earner narrative, and post-PE-rollover equity for agency principals whose practices have been acquired by Acrisure, USI, HUB International, Brown &amp; Brown, or other consolidator platforms</strong>. A new-licensed agent in years 1-2 building book of business, an established captive agent at State Farm with stable W-2, an established independent P&amp;C agent at $200K Schedule C, an agency principal with sub-producer override, and a multi-line MDRT life producer each get qualified using methods that fit their actual structure. Or skip ahead: browse <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/" style="color: var(--blue); text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 2px;">every loan program</a>, run numbers on <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-calculator/" style="color: var(--blue); text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 2px;">100+ mortgage calculators</a>, or check <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/current-rates/" style="color: var(--blue); text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 2px;">today&apos;s rates</a>. For the parent hub and other sales professional paths, see our <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/sales-professionals/" style="color: var(--blue); text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 2px;">sales professionals mortgage hub</a>.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ H2 #1: KEY FACTS ============ -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header" style="text-align: center; max-width: 760px; margin: 0 auto;">
        <div class="eyebrow">01 &middot; Insurance agent mortgage at a glance</div>
        <h2>Key facts every insurance agent should know before applying for a mortgage.</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="key-facts-grid">
        <div class="key-fact-card">
          <div class="key-fact-num">Channel matters</div>
          <p class="key-fact-body">The captive vs independent channel distinction is the single biggest qualifying variable. Captive agents at State Farm, Allstate, Farmers, Liberty Mutual, and Nationwide receive W-2 income qualifying under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">B3-3.1-01</a>. Independent agents at Brown &amp; Brown, HUB, USI, Acrisure, and regional agencies receive 1099-NEC Schedule C commission qualifying under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.3-02/income-analysis-self-employed-borrowers" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">B3-3.3-02</a>.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="key-fact-card">
          <div class="key-fact-num">Renewal income</div>
          <p class="key-fact-body">Multi-year renewal and residual commission income on existing books of business is the stability foundation under variable new business. P&amp;C renewals typically pay 5-15% of renewing premiums; life/annuity renewals are lower after year 1 but persistent. Renewal income substantially exceeds new business commission for established agents after 3-5+ years building book.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="key-fact-card">
          <div class="key-fact-num">NAIC / state DOI</div>
          <p class="key-fact-body">Insurance agent licensing is regulated state-by-state through each state Department of Insurance with model laws coordinated through the <a href="https://www.naic.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">National Association of Insurance Commissioners (NAIC)</a>. License lines split: P&amp;C (Property &amp; Casualty), Life/Health, Variable Lines (requires Series 6 or Series 7), and Surplus Lines.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="key-fact-card">
          <div class="key-fact-num">Trade orgs</div>
          <p class="key-fact-body">Major insurance industry trade organizations include <a href="https://www.naifa.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">NAIFA (National Association of Insurance &amp; Financial Advisors)</a> for life producers, <a href="https://www.independentagent.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Big "I" (Independent Insurance Agents &amp; Brokers of America)</a> for P&amp;C independents, and <a href="https://www.mdrt.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Million Dollar Round Table (MDRT)</a> for elite life producers.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ H2 #2: ROLE-STAGE SOLUTIONS ============ -->
  <section class="professions-section section-tinted">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header" style="text-align: center; max-width: 720px; margin: 0 auto;">
        <div class="eyebrow">02 &middot; Where you are in your insurance career</div>
        <h2>Insurance agent mortgage solutions for every career stage.</h2>
        <p>Each stage of an insurance agent career has its own qualifying logic. A new-licensed agent in years 1-2 building book of business has a different mortgage path than an established captive agent at State Farm or Allstate with stable W-2, an independent agent at $200K Schedule C, an agency principal with sub-producer override, or a multi-line MDRT life producer at $400K+.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="professions-grid">

        <a class="profession-card" href="#income-methods">
          <div class="profession-num">01</div>
          <h3 class="profession-title">New-licensed agent (Years 1&ndash;2)</h3>
          <p class="profession-tag">"Recently licensed insurance agent at state Department of Insurance. Building first book of business at captive (State Farm, Allstate, Farmers) or independent agency. Limited 2-year history."</p>
          <ul class="profession-points">
            <li>Annual income $50K&ndash;$95K W-2 base + ramping commission (captive)</li>
            <li>OR $40K&ndash;$80K projected Schedule C at independent agency</li>
            <li>2-year history not yet established for sole qualifying</li>
            <li>Conventional with co-borrower (typically spouse W-2)</li>
          </ul>
          <span class="profession-link">See new-agent mechanics</span>
        </a>

        <a class="profession-card" href="#income-methods">
          <div class="profession-num">02</div>
          <h3 class="profession-title">Established captive agent</h3>
          <p class="profession-tag">"Established W-2 captive agent at State Farm, Allstate, Farmers, American Family, Liberty Mutual, or Nationwide. Stable base salary plus commission plus production bonus on book of business 3+ years old."</p>
          <ul class="profession-points">
            <li>Annual income $130K&ndash;$300K W-2 base + commission + bonus</li>
            <li>2-year history supports full B3-3.1-01 variable income qualifying</li>
            <li>Renewal income embedded in commission stream</li>
            <li>Conventional Conforming with W-2 documentation</li>
          </ul>
          <span class="profession-link">See captive agent mechanics</span>
        </a>

        <a class="profession-card" href="#income-methods">
          <div class="profession-num">03</div>
          <h3 class="profession-title">Established independent agent</h3>
          <p class="profession-tag">"Established 1099 independent agent at Brown &amp; Brown, Marsh McLennan Agency, HUB International, USI, Acrisure, AssuredPartners, or regional independent agency. Multi-carrier flexibility with customer ownership."</p>
          <ul class="profession-points">
            <li>Annual income $150K&ndash;$400K Schedule C 1099 commission + renewals</li>
            <li>Independent channel net commission higher than captive (no carrier split)</li>
            <li>B3-3.3-02 with 2-year averaging plus Form 1084 addbacks</li>
            <li>Bank Statement Non-QM alternative for high-deduction agents</li>
          </ul>
          <span class="profession-link">See independent agent mechanics</span>
        </a>

        <a class="profession-card" href="#income-methods">
          <div class="profession-num">04</div>
          <h3 class="profession-title">Agency principal / owner</h3>
          <p class="profession-tag">"Owner of independent insurance agency in S-corp structure. Combines personal production with sub-producer override (typically 20-40% of sub-producer commission) plus carrier profit-sharing distributions tied to loss ratios."</p>
          <ul class="profession-points">
            <li>Annual income $250K&ndash;$1M+ through S-corp ownership</li>
            <li>S-corp W-2 reasonable comp + K-1 distributions under B3-3.4-02</li>
            <li>Carrier profit sharing + sub-producer override layers</li>
            <li>Book-of-business asset value supports reserve documentation</li>
          </ul>
          <span class="profession-link">See agency principal mechanics</span>
        </a>

        <a class="profession-card" href="#income-methods">
          <div class="profession-num">05</div>
          <h3 class="profession-title">Multi-line / commercial / MDRT specialist</h3>
          <p class="profession-tag">"Multi-line insurance specialist (P&amp;C + life + health + commercial) holding multiple state licenses plus Series 6 or Series 7 for variable annuity products. May be on MDRT Top of the Table for life production. Higher tier income."</p>
          <ul class="profession-points">
            <li>Annual income $300K&ndash;$1M+ across multiple product lines</li>
            <li>CPCU, CIC, CLU, ChFC, CFP, MDRT credentials</li>
            <li>Multi-source Schedule C across product line categories</li>
            <li>Conventional Jumbo with credentials documentation</li>
          </ul>
          <span class="profession-link">See multi-line specialist mechanics</span>
        </a>

      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ H2 #3: INCOME CALCULATION METHODS ============ -->
  <section class="section" id="income-methods">
    <div class="container-narrow">
      <div class="section-header">
        <div class="eyebrow">03 &middot; The qualification mechanics</div>
        <h2>How we calculate qualifying income for your insurance agent mortgage.</h2>
        <p>Four methods cover almost every insurance agent file we&rsquo;ve closed. The right method depends on your channel (captive W-2 vs independent 1099), your product line mix (P&amp;C vs life vs health vs commercial), whether you operate as agency principal with override income, and whether you have made the S-corp election.</p>
      </div>

      <h3>Method 1 &mdash; Captive agent W-2 + commission + bonus (the captive default)</h3>
      <p>The dominant pattern for captive agents at State Farm, Allstate, Farmers Insurance, American Family Insurance, Liberty Mutual, Nationwide Insurance, and similar carrier-employed agency models. Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Fannie Mae B3-3.1-01</a>, captive W-2 base salary plus commission income plus production bonus qualifies as variable income with 24-month average. Captive carriers typically structure commission at 8-15% of new business premium plus 5-10% trailing renewal commission, with year-end production bonus tied to retention, growth, and loss-ratio metrics. The 24-month average smooths year-over-year variation and provides solid qualifying foundation for established captive agents. Renewal income embedded in W-2 commission stream provides natural stability that underwriters recognize positively.</p>

      <h3>Method 2 &mdash; Independent agent Schedule C + Form 1084 addbacks (the independent default)</h3>
      <p>The dominant pattern for independent agents at Brown &amp; Brown, Marsh McLennan Agency (MMA), HUB International, USI Insurance Services, Acrisure, AssuredPartners, regional independent agencies, and thousands of local independent shops. Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.3-02/income-analysis-self-employed-borrowers" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Fannie Mae B3-3.3-02</a>, independent agent Schedule C 1099 commission income qualifies with 2-year averaging plus Form 1084 cash-flow addbacks. Independent channel commission tier typically runs 12-25% on P&amp;C new business plus 10-20% trailing renewal commission, with higher percentages reflecting absence of carrier-employed structure overhead. Independent agents take substantial Schedule C deductions for office expense, vehicle, marketing, leads, professional designation continuing education, and E&amp;O insurance &mdash; Form 1084 systematically restores non-cash items under <a href="https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/26/167" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">IRC Section 167</a> depreciation.</p>

      <h3>Method 3 &mdash; Agency principal S-corp + sub-producer override + profit sharing</h3>
      <p>For agency principals operating independent agencies as S-corp owner-operators with sub-producers. Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.4-02/analyzing-returns-partnership-or-s-corporation" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Fannie Mae B3-3.4-02</a>, qualifying income combines S-corp W-2 reasonable compensation (typically $110K-$170K for agency principals) plus K-1 distributions from <a href="https://www.irs.gov/forms-pubs/about-form-1120-s" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Form 1120-S</a> reflecting personal production plus sub-producer override (typically 20-40% of sub-producer commission) plus carrier profit-sharing distributions tied to agency portfolio loss ratios. Form 1084 cash-flow addbacks at S-corp level recover non-cash deductions for agency property depreciation, equipment, and amortization. Insurance agency operations are NOT classified as SSTB under <a href="https://www.irs.gov/businesses/qualified-business-income-deduction" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">IRC Section 199A</a> &mdash; qualifying for 20% QBI deduction subject to wage limitations.</p>

      <h3>Method 4 &mdash; Multi-line specialist multi-source aggregation</h3>
      <p>For multi-line insurance specialists holding multiple state licenses (P&amp;C plus Life/Health) plus securities licensing (Series 6 for mutual funds and variable annuities, Series 7 for full securities, Series 63/65 for state advisory) plus professional designations (CPCU, CIC, CLU, ChFC, CFP). Multi-line specialists commonly aggregate income across P&amp;C 1099 commission, life insurance 1099 commission (often high first-year on whole life, IUL, universal life, variable life products), Medicare Advantage/Supplement enrollment commission with AEP seasonal cycle, annuity production commission (sometimes 5-7% of annuity premium for fixed indexed annuities), and investment advisory fees if RIA-licensed. Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.3-02/income-analysis-self-employed-borrowers" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">B3-3.3-02</a>, multi-source aggregation requires documentation of each product line stream with 2-year history. MDRT Top of the Table credentialing supports elite-tier income narrative.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ H2 #4: DARK SECTION ============ -->
  <section class="per-diem-section per-diem-section--bg" style="background-image: url('https://images.pexels.com/photos/5668858/pexels-photo-5668858.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=1800');">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header" style="max-width: 760px;">
        <div class="eyebrow eyebrow-light">04 &middot; What generalist underwriting misses</div>
        <h2 style="color: var(--paper);">The income most lenders refuse to count on an insurance agent file.</h2>
        <p style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.78);">Six income facts that show up consistently on working insurance agent files and that generalist lenders typically either ignore, mis-categorize, or refuse to apply correctly. Each one is documentable; the lender just has to read the insurance multi-stream pattern properly.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="dark-grid">
        <div class="dark-card">
          <div class="dark-num">A</div>
          <h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">Channel-specific income classification (captive W-2 vs independent 1099)</h3>
          <p class="dark-card-body" style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.72);">Captive agents at State Farm, Allstate, Farmers, Liberty Mutual, Nationwide receive W-2 commission qualifying under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--blue-soft);">B3-3.1-01</a>. Independent agents at Brown &amp; Brown, HUB, USI, Acrisure, AssuredPartners receive 1099-NEC Schedule C commission qualifying under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.3-02/income-analysis-self-employed-borrowers" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--blue-soft);">B3-3.3-02</a> with Form 1084 addbacks. Generalist lenders sometimes apply wrong rule to wrong channel or fail to recognize channel transitions when an agent has moved from captive to independent mid-period.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="dark-card">
          <div class="dark-num">B</div>
          <h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">Multi-year renewal and residual commission income</h3>
          <p class="dark-card-body" style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.72);">Multi-year renewal income on existing book of business is the stability foundation under variable new business commission. P&amp;C renewals typically pay 5-15% of renewing premiums in year 2+; life insurance renewals lower after year 1 but persistent; commercial renewals strong. For established agents 5+ years building book, renewal income commonly exceeds new business commission and provides the predictable annuity-like stream that generalist underwriters often classify as "variable not stable" rather than the recurring revenue it actually is.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="dark-card">
          <div class="dark-num">C</div>
          <h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">Carrier profit-sharing distributions (loss-ratio-based)</h3>
          <p class="dark-card-body" style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.72);">Independent agencies receive profit-sharing distributions from carriers tied to agency portfolio loss ratios (typically annual distributions based on prior-year loss-ratio performance vs threshold). Profit sharing commonly runs 0.5-3% of premium volume placed with the carrier, producing $25K-$200K+ annually for established independent agencies. Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.3-02/income-analysis-self-employed-borrowers" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--blue-soft);">B3-3.3-02</a>, profit sharing qualifies as continuing Schedule C self-employment with 2-year history. Generalist lenders often misclassify as "discretionary bonus not stable."</p>
        </div>
        <div class="dark-card">
          <div class="dark-num">D</div>
          <h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">Book-of-business asset value (1.5x-3x annual revenue)</h3>
          <p class="dark-card-body" style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.72);">Independent insurance agency books of business carry asset value typically 1.5x to 3x annual revenue based on retention rates, product mix, and portfolio quality. Acrisure, USI, HUB International, Brown &amp; Brown, and other PE-backed consolidators routinely acquire books in this multiple range. For agency principals, the book-of-business equity supports reserve documentation under conventional qualifying and asset-depletion calculations. The book carries asset value not visible on personal tax returns.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="dark-card">
          <div class="dark-num">E</div>
          <h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">Medicare AEP seasonal spike + Annual recurring revenue (ARR) dynamics</h3>
          <p class="dark-card-body" style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.72);">Agents specializing in Medicare Advantage and Medicare Supplement enrollment have Annual Enrollment Period (AEP, October 15 to December 7) production cycles that create Q4-heavy commission distribution. Medicare Advantage commission typically $200-$500 per enrollment plus renewal commission in subsequent years. Top Medicare agents commonly enroll 200-800+ Medicare beneficiaries annually generating $50K-$400K of AEP-cycle income plus building book ARR. Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.3-02/income-analysis-self-employed-borrowers" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--blue-soft);">B3-3.3-02</a>, the 2-year average smooths AEP seasonality.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="dark-card">
          <div class="dark-num">F</div>
          <h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">Agency principal sub-producer override income</h3>
          <p class="dark-card-body" style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.72);">Agency principals at independent agencies earn override on sub-producer commission, typically 20-40% of sub-producer commission revenue. For an agency principal with 3-5 sub-producers each generating $150K-$250K annually, override income commonly adds $250K-$500K+ on top of personal production. Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.4-02/analyzing-returns-partnership-or-s-corporation" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--blue-soft);">Fannie Mae B3-3.4-02</a>, override income flows through S-corp K-1 distributions and qualifies with 2-year history. Generalist lenders often miss this stream or classify it incorrectly.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ H2 #5: LOAN PROGRAM MATRIX ============ -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header" style="text-align: center; max-width: 720px; margin: 0 auto;">
