        <h2>Insurance agent mortgage by career stage.</h2>
        <p>A timeline view of how the right mortgage program changes as you progress from new-licensed agent through established captive or independent producer to agency principal or multi-line MDRT specialist.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="career-timeline">

        <div class="timeline-entry">
          <div class="timeline-stage">Years 1&ndash;2</div>
          <div class="timeline-body">
            <h4>New-licensed agent</h4>
            <p><strong>Comp profile:</strong> $50K&ndash;$95K W-2 base salary plus ramping commission at captive carrier, OR $40K&ndash;$80K projected Schedule C at independent agency with strong mentor. <strong>Dominant qualifying method:</strong> Conventional with W-2 documentation plus possible co-borrower (spouse W-2) for early-career independent agents with limited Schedule C history. <strong>Common purchase:</strong> $350K&ndash;$550K with co-borrower support. <strong>Watch-out:</strong> State Department of Insurance licensure must be active across all required lines; no compliance issues.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="timeline-entry">
          <div class="timeline-stage">Years 3&ndash;7</div>
          <div class="timeline-body">
            <h4>Established captive or independent agent</h4>
            <p><strong>Comp profile:</strong> $130K&ndash;$300K captive W-2 (base + commission + bonus) OR $150K&ndash;$400K independent Schedule C with established 2-year history including renewal stream from established book. <strong>Dominant qualifying method:</strong> Conventional Conforming or Jumbo with B3-3.1-01 captive W-2 OR B3-3.3-02 Schedule C with Form 1084. <strong>Common purchase:</strong> $600K&ndash;$1M primary residence. <strong>Watch-out:</strong> Renewal income should be documented as continuing stream &mdash; many underwriters treat it as variable when it&rsquo;s actually the most stable component.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="timeline-entry">
          <div class="timeline-stage">Agency principal / owner</div>
          <div class="timeline-body">
            <h4>Agency principal / owner</h4>
            <p><strong>Comp profile:</strong> $250K&ndash;$1M+ through S-corp combining personal production plus sub-producer override (20-40% of sub-producer commission) plus carrier profit-sharing distributions. <strong>Dominant qualifying method:</strong> Conventional Jumbo with B3-3.4-02 S-corp documentation plus Form 1084 addbacks at entity level. <strong>Common purchase:</strong> $900K&ndash;$1.6M primary residence. <strong>Watch-out:</strong> Sub-producer override structure requires proper documentation through agency&rsquo;s sub-producer agreements and 1099-NEC override receipts.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="timeline-entry">
          <div class="timeline-stage">Multi-line / MDRT / post-PE-sale</div>
          <div class="timeline-body">
            <h4>Multi-line specialist or post-PE-sale principal</h4>
            <p><strong>Comp profile:</strong> $400K&ndash;$2M+ through multi-line aggregation (P&amp;C + life + health + commercial + annuity + advisory), MDRT Top of the Table life production, or post-PE-sale rollover equity from agency principal acquisition by Acrisure / HUB / USI / Brown &amp; Brown / Marsh McLennan Agency consolidator. <strong>Dominant qualifying method:</strong> Conventional Super-Jumbo with multi-entity documentation or Asset-Depletion Non-QM for post-sale principals with significant liquid reserves. <strong>Common purchase:</strong> $1.2M&ndash;$3M+ primary residence. <strong>Watch-out:</strong> Post-PE-sale rollover equity + multi-year earnouts require multi-source documentation similar to post-PE-sale veterinarian or other practice-sale scenarios.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

