        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">01</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">I&rsquo;m a captive agent at State Farm. How does my W-2 commission and bonus qualify?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Captive agent W-2 base salary plus commission plus production bonus qualifies under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Fannie Mae B3-3.1-01</a> as variable income with 24-month average. The W-2 structure at captive carriers is well-understood by experienced underwriters. We document the production bonus formula and multi-year continuity to support the full income component as continuing.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">02</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">I&rsquo;m an independent agent. My Schedule C income includes heavy deductions for leads, office, vehicle, and E&amp;O. Can I still qualify?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Yes &mdash; this is exactly what Form 1084 cash-flow analysis under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.3-02/income-analysis-self-employed-borrowers" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">B3-3.3-02</a> addresses. Vehicle depreciation, home office depreciation, equipment depreciation, and amortization items are non-cash deductions that Form 1084 systematically adds back. E&amp;O insurance, marketing, leads, and CE expense remain cash deductions but don&rsquo;t get addback treatment. For working independent agents, Form 1084 commonly recovers $25K-$70K of qualifying income above Schedule C Line 31.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">03</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My renewal income on my P&amp;C book is more stable than new business. Does the underwriter understand that?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Yes when properly documented. Renewal commission income (typically 5-15% on P&amp;C renewals; lower on life renewals after year 1) qualifies under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">B3-3.1-01</a> for captive W-2 or <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.3-02/income-analysis-self-employed-borrowers" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">B3-3.3-02</a> for independent Schedule C as continuing variable income with 24-month average. For established agents 5+ years, renewal income commonly provides annuity-like stability that supports strong qualifying. We document the renewal income separately from new business commission.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">04</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">I&rsquo;m an agency principal. My carrier profit-sharing distributions vary with loss-ratio years. Will the underwriter count them?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Yes with 2-year history. Carrier profit-sharing distributions tied to agency portfolio loss ratios (typically 0.5-3% of premium volume placed) aggregate as continuing Schedule C self-employment income under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.3-02/income-analysis-self-employed-borrowers" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">B3-3.3-02</a> with 2-year history. The 2-year average smooths catastrophe-year volatility. We document the historical profit-sharing pattern across carriers in your appointment portfolio.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">05</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">I&rsquo;m on MDRT Top of the Table for life insurance production. Does that help qualifying?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Indirectly &mdash; MDRT Top of the Table credentialing (top tier of <a href="https://www.mdrt.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Million Dollar Round Table</a>) supports the high-tier life producer income narrative for underwriting context. For top life producers at $400K-$1M+ annual income, MDRT credentialing provides industry-recognized documentation of production tier that helps underwriters contextualize the income level.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">06</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">What documentation do I need for an insurance agent mortgage?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Typically: two complete federal 1040s with all schedules including Schedule C if independent agent; if S-corp agency principal, Form 1120-S returns with K-1s; all W-2s if captive agent; all 1099-NECs from carriers if independent; current state Department of Insurance licensure for all license lines; carrier appointment documentation; sub-producer agreements if agency principal; book-of-business reports showing renewal income detail; 60 days of personal and business bank statements; professional designation documentation (CPCU, CIC, CLU, ChFC, CFP); MDRT credentialing if applicable.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">07</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My Medicare AEP commission is concentrated in Q4. How does the underwriter handle seasonality?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Annual Enrollment Period (AEP, October 15 to December 7) creates Q4-heavy commission cycle for Medicare-focused agents. Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.3-02/income-analysis-self-employed-borrowers" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">B3-3.3-02</a>, the 2-year average smooths the AEP seasonality. Medicare commission per enrollment ($200-$500 typical) plus renewal commission in subsequent years aggregates with other product line income.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">08</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">When should I make S-corp election for my insurance agency?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Typically at $200K-$300K+ of annual net Schedule C income, S-corp election starts producing meaningful self-employment tax savings. Particularly relevant for agency principals with sub-producers where the S-corp structure cleanly handles the override income flow. Coordinate timing with your CPA &mdash; the election typically must be made by March 15 for the current tax year.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">09</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My agency is being acquired by a PE-backed consolidator (Acrisure / HUB / USI). How does that affect my mortgage qualifying?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">PE acquisitions typically structure transactions with cash up front, multi-year earnouts, rollover equity in the holding entity, and ongoing W-2 employment. Post-sale qualifying aggregates ongoing W-2 under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">B3-3.1-01</a>, rollover equity K-1 under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.4-02/analyzing-returns-partnership-or-s-corporation" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">B3-3.4-02</a>, and earnout consideration with multi-year payment schedule documentation. Strategic timing: close mortgage BEFORE sale on established S-corp K-1 history, or AFTER sale with multi-source post-acquisition picture &mdash; we model both scenarios.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">10</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">I&rsquo;m a multi-line specialist. My income mixes P&amp;C + life + annuity + Medicare. How is that documented?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Multi-line specialist income aggregates across product line categories with documentation showing each stream&rsquo;s 2-year history. Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.3-02/income-analysis-self-employed-borrowers" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">B3-3.3-02</a>, we document carrier appointments, 1099-NEC receipts across product lines, professional designation credentials supporting each license category, and book-of-business reports showing renewal stream by product line. Top multi-line specialists commonly aggregate $300K-$1M+ across the product mix.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">11</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Are mortgage rates higher for insurance agents?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">No &mdash; mortgage rates for insurance agents are the same as for any other borrower at the same credit profile, loan amount, and program selection. The qualifying mechanics determine outcome, not the borrower&rsquo;s industry. We work through standard pricing competitively.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">12</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My book of business has $4M of annual revenue. Does that count as an asset?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Indirectly. Book-of-business asset value (typically 1.5x-3x annual revenue for established independent agencies based on retention and quality) is a business asset on the agency&rsquo;s balance sheet, not personal liquid assets. The book value supports the agency principal&rsquo;s business creditworthiness and may support asset-depletion calculations, but doesn&rsquo;t count directly as personal reserves. Liquid reserves at the agency entity level count if accessible for distribution.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">13</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My spouse is also an insurance agent (or related sales). How does that affect us?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Two-agent or insurance+sales households produce strong joint qualifying when both spouses have established 2-year histories. Both files combine as co-borrowers with full B3-3.1-01 (captive W-2) or B3-3.3-02 (independent Schedule C) analysis on each spouse. Joint income commonly $300K-$800K supports $1M-$2M qualifying. Many insurance + insurance households also have book-of-business reserves supporting jumbo qualifying.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">14</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">I just transitioned from captive (Allstate) to independent agency. How do I qualify?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Channel transitions create documentation complexity. The new-channel Schedule C history at independent agency doesn&rsquo;t yet meet B3-3.3-02 2-year requirement. Alternative paths: (1) extend documentation including prior captive W-2 history as continuing employment in same profession, arguing for combined qualifying under B3-3.1-01 + B3-3.3-02 with continuity documentation; (2) Bank Statement Program Non-QM using 12-24 months of current independent agent bank statements; (3) wait until 2-year independent history establishes. We model the options.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">15</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My agency has E&amp;O insurance and bond. Does that affect qualifying?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Indirectly. Active E&amp;O (Errors and Omissions) insurance and any state-required bond coverage support the agency&rsquo;s professional standing and operational compliance, contributing to underwriter comfort. The premiums are Schedule C deductions that affect net income calculation. We document the active coverage at application time.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">16</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Can a co-borrower help me qualify?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Yes, significantly. Co-borrower files combine W-2s, 1099s, Schedule C, and S-corp distributions from both parties. For new-licensed agents in years 1-2 where income is still establishing, a co-borrower with stable W-2 income often substantially helps qualifying ratios.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">17</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My S-corp agency has retained earnings. Are those usable as reserves?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Generally yes if accessible. S-corp retained earnings in agency business accounts count as reserves if you have ability to distribute them. Documented via 1120-S Schedule L (balance sheet). For established agency principals with 5+ years of accumulated retained earnings, reserve strength supports jumbo qualifying.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">18</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">How does the IRS Section 199A QBI deduction affect me as an insurance agency principal?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Insurance brokerage operations are generally NOT classified as SSTB under <a href="https://www.irs.gov/businesses/qualified-business-income-deduction" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">IRC Section 199A</a>. Insurance agency operations qualify for the 20% QBI deduction subject to wage limitations at higher income. This is favorable vs medical/dental/legal SSTB-classified professionals.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">19</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">I&rsquo;m considering acquiring another independent agency. How does that fit with personal mortgage?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Insurance agency acquisitions typically run $200K-$5M+ depending on book size, retention, and product mix. <a href="https://www.sba.gov/funding-programs/loans/7a-loans" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">SBA 7(a)</a> financing up to $5M is common for agency acquisitions. We sequence personal mortgage either BEFORE acquisition closes (qualifying on established agency Schedule C history) or AFTER acquisition integrates 12-18 months post-acquisition with combined-agency K-1 history.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">20</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My commercial insurance book has large per-account commissions ($5K-$50K each). Does that affect 2-year averaging?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Commercial insurance income volatility (driven by large per-account commission events) creates 2-year averages that smooth across the period. The 2-year B3-3.3-02 average accommodates this pattern well for established commercial producers with consistent overall pipeline. We document the commercial account portfolio and the renewal stream to support continuing income narrative.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">21</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Are there mortgage programs specifically designed for insurance agents?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">No specialty insurance-agent-specific products are widely available. What matters is finding a broker who understands channel-specific qualifying mechanics: B3-3.1-01 captive W-2, B3-3.3-02 independent Schedule C with Form 1084 addbacks, B3-3.4-02 S-corp agency principal with sub-producer override and profit sharing, and the renewal-income recognition that distinguishes established agents from variable-income generic borrowers.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">22</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Can I use bank statements alone instead of tax returns?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Yes through Bank Statement Program Non-QM products for independent agents whose Schedule C deductions suppress tax return income that Form 1084 addbacks can&rsquo;t fully restore. 12 or 24 months of business bank statements qualify under the Bank Statement Non-QM framework. Pricing carries 0.75-1.5% rate premium vs Conventional. Useful for high-deduction independent agents or post-record-year scenarios.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">23</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My state DOI license has been active for 8 years with no complaints. Does that help?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Indirectly &mdash; active multi-year state Department of Insurance licensure with no compliance issues supports the professional standing narrative for underwriting context. <a href="https://www.naic.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">NAIC</a> coordinates model laws but state DOI databases are public-record verification. We confirm active status at application time.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">24</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">When should I start the mortgage conversation relative to a home purchase?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Ideally 90-120 days before you intend to make an offer. Insurance agent files benefit from runway because of channel-specific income classification, multi-component documentation across product lines, Form 1084 cash-flow analysis for independent agents, possible S-corp 1120-S review for agency principals, and renewal income stream documentation. For agency principals considering PE consolidator acquisition offers, additional runway helps coordinate mortgage close timing with transaction timing.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">25</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Why do generalist lenders refuse insurance agent files when income is clearly there?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Five reasons: (1) channel-specific income classification confusion (applying captive W-2 rules to independent 1099 Schedule C or vice versa); (2) renewal income classified as "variable not stable" rather than properly recognized as the recurring revenue annuity it actually is; (3) carrier profit-sharing distributions refused as "discretionary loss-ratio bonus" rather than properly aggregated under B3-3.3-02 with 2-year history; (4) sub-producer override for agency principals missed or mis-categorized; (5) multi-line specialist income across P&amp;C + life + Medicare + annuity overwhelms generalist underwriters. The income is all there and verifiable &mdash; the file just needs a broker who reads insurance agent multi-stream structure correctly.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

