        <div class="eyebrow">12 &middot; What "right door first" looks like</div>
        <h2>Insurance agent mortgage, structured right.</h2>
        <p>Independent agency principal for 12 years operating an S-corp insurance agency with 4 sub-producer agents underneath, multi-line book combining P&amp;C personal lines, commercial P&amp;C, and life/annuity. S-corp W-2 reasonable compensation $145K plus K-1 distributions $275K reflecting personal production (35% of K-1) plus sub-producer override at 30% of $620K aggregate sub-producer commission revenue (52% of K-1) plus carrier profit-sharing distributions $42K from established carrier appointments tied to 24-month favorable loss-ratio performance (13% of K-1). Total $462K across the W-2 plus K-1 components. Book of business approximately $4.2M annual revenue with retention rate 94% and 5-year compound growth rate of 8%. Active state Department of Insurance licensure across P&amp;C and Life/Health lines plus carrier appointments with 6 primary carriers. The first lender saw the multi-component income structure on the S-corp 1120-S and 1040, called the sub-producer override "management variable bonus not stable production income," refused the carrier profit-sharing as "loss-ratio-dependent and irregular," didn&rsquo;t run Form 1084 cash-flow addbacks at the S-corp level to recover non-cash depreciation on agency property and equipment, and offered the principal $685K Conventional Conforming based on the S-corp W-2 reasonable comp of $145K alone. They missed that the B3-3.4-02 framework specifically aggregates S-corp W-2 plus K-1 distributions as continuing income with 2-year 1120-S history, that sub-producer override is contractually structured continuing income through documented sub-producer agreements, and that carrier profit-sharing with 2+ year continuity is continuing self-employment under B3-3.3-02 even if the dollar amount fluctuates with loss ratios. We pulled the S-corp 1120-S returns for 2022, 2023, and 2024 with all K-1s, the agency&rsquo;s sub-producer agreements documenting the 30% override structure across all 4 sub-producers, the carrier profit-sharing statements showing 2-year favorable distribution pattern across 6 appointed carriers, the personal 1040 with Schedule B (interest/dividends) reflecting business account income, the state Department of Insurance licensure across all required license lines, and the carrier appointment documentation. Ran the consolidated S-corp W-2 plus K-1 under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.4-02/analyzing-returns-partnership-or-s-corporation" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--blue);">Fannie Mae B3-3.4-02</a> with full Form 1084 cash-flow analysis at the S-corp level recovering vehicle depreciation, agency property depreciation, equipment depreciation, and amortization. Documented the sub-producer override through the sub-producer agreements and 2-year override receipt history. Aggregated carrier profit-sharing as continuing Schedule C self-employment under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.3-02/income-analysis-self-employed-borrowers" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--blue);">B3-3.3-02</a> with 2-year continuity documentation across all appointed carriers. Total qualifying income after Form 1084 normalization: $425K. Approved at $1.45M Conventional Jumbo for a Weston home in 44 days. Multi-component agency principal income with sub-producer override + carrier profit sharing is the standard established-principal pattern &mdash; the first lender just didn&rsquo;t know how to read agency principal multi-source structure properly.</p>
      </div>
